\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I present four main findings that apply to the period 1997-2012:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Effective inventors have become more concentrated in specific technology
 classes and economic sectors;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Sectors with increased concentration have attracted a growing share of relevant
 inventor types.
 The IV analysis suggest that the rise in inventor shares is the result,
 and not the cause, of increased concentration;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Growth in the share of relevant inventors is negatively correlated with
 inventor productivity, as measured by average growth in output per workers
 divided by effective inventors employed;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Growth in the share of relevant inventors is positively correlated with
 the share of self-citations and excess self-citations, as well as concentration
 of inventors at the top within sectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first finding emerges from the computation of Gini coefficients of effective
 inventors across technologies and sectors.
 Findings 2-4 come from long-difference regressions over the period 1997-2012.
 Regressions are weighted by sector sales in 2012 for findings 2-3, which
 rely on Census sector-level measures, with robust standard errors.
 I present both unweighted and unweighted results for finding 4, since these
 variables do not represent aggregates according to sales, and rely on patent
 data only.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For findings 2-4, I run long-difference regressions at the product market
 level for the period 1997-2012:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta\text{Outcome}{}_{p}=\beta\Delta\text{Indep.Var.}_{p}+\gamma'\Delta\text{Controls}_{p}+\varepsilon_{p},\label{eq: spec}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

